article.headline: Governors hold off late rally
article.linkText: Late 11-0 run spurs Austin Peay past Belmont
article.story: CLARKSVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Austin Peay had an 11-0 run over a two-minute stretch late in the second half, then weathered a rally by Belmont in the final minute and held on for a 65-59 victory in the opening round of the NIT on Wednesday night. The Governors (22-9), regular-season champions of the Ohio Valley Conference, scored their final 14 points during a span of 1:40 to extend their home winning streak to 29 games. Belmont (21-9) rallied in the final 40 seconds, thanks to three 3-point baskets that pulled the Bruins to within 59-57 with 19 seconds left. However, the Governors, who attempted 30 free throws to just four for the Bruins, were able to hold on for the win by making their final six foul shots -- two each by Josh Lewis, Adrian Henning and Corey Gipson. Henning led Austin Peay with 15 points, and Anthony Davis added 14. Belmont's Adam Mark led all scorers with 19 points, while Steve Drabyn added 12 -- all on 3-pointers. Both teams were playing in the NIT for the first time. The Governors will move on to the first round to face George Mason, which defeated Tennessee 58-55 Wednesday night. The Governors' 11-0 run began when Rhet Wierzba's 3-pointer with 3:28 left gave them a 49-48 lead. Austin Peay capped the run on Davis' two free throws with 52.3 seconds to play.
